:[{\"id\":75771,\"cargo\":{\"descricao\":\"Auditor Federal de Controle Externo - \u00c1rea Controle Externo\",\"id\":12103,\"slug\":\"auditor-federal-de-controle-externo-area-controle-externo\"},\"orgao\":{\"nome\":\"Tribunal de Contas da Uni\u00e3o\",\"sigla\":\"TCU\",\"id\":1101,\"esfera\":\"Federal\",\"uf\":\"BR\",\"slug\":\"tcu\"},\"banca\":{\"nome\":\"Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas\",\"descricao\":\"Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Get\u00falio Vargas - FGV\",\"sigla\":\"FGV\",\"oab\":true,\"id\":102,\"slug\":\"fgv\"},\"ano\":2022,\"nivel\":\"Superior\",\"slug\":\"tcu-2022-fgv-auditor-federal-de-controle-externo-area-controle-externo\",\"tipo\":1,\"nome\":\"FGV - TCU - Auditor Federal de Controle Externo - \u00c1rea Controle Externo - 2022\"}],\"comentarios\":{\"professor\":false,\"professorVideo\":false,\"aluno\":false,\"totalAlunos\":0,\"totalProfessores\":0},\"timestamp\":\"2022-06-28 22:16:55\",\"carreiras\":[{\"nome\":\"Controle e Gest\u00e3o\",\"descricao\":\"Cargos de Controle e de Gest\u00e3o P\u00fablicos\",\"id\":57},{\"nome\":\"Controle e Gest\u00e3o  Controle (Tribunais de Contas, Controladorias Internas)\",\"descricao\":\"Cargos de Controle (Tribunais de Contas e Controladorias Internas), pois os TCs fazem o chamado controle externo, sendo os TCEs, \u00e2mbito estadual, e TCU, no federal. J\u00e1 controladorias seria um termo gen\u00e9rico pra ilustrar todo o controle interno, pois todo \u00f3rg\u00e3o, seja ele do PE, PJ, PL, DP e MP, possui controle interno. A\u00ed os nomes v\u00e3o variar: CGU, CGEs, Analista ou Gestor ou Auditor de Controle Interno da Prefeitura X, da Assembl\u00e9ia Legislativa Z, etc\",\"id\":67}],\"areas\":[{\"id\":276,\"descricao\":\"N\u00edvel Superior Em Qualquer \u00c1rea\"}],\"id\":2287748,\"hashId\":\"6cab8f6005a0979f96577ad25ec2d5b7\",\"enunciado\":\"<p style=text-align: justify;>The function of the extract \u201ci.e., risks associated with how organizations operate in respect to their impact on the world around them\u201d (fourth paragraph) is to:<p>\",\"resposta\":9014585,\"anulada\":false,\"rotulo\":15,\"desatualizada\":false,\"itens\":[{\"corpo_clean\":\"indicate expected results;\",\"id\":9014582,\"corpo\":\"<p>indicate expected results;<p>\",\"ordem\":1,\"rotulo\":\"A\"},{\"corpo_clean\":\"add contrasting information;\",\"id\":9014583,\"corpo\":\"<p>add contrasting information;<p>\",\"ordem\":2,\"rotulo\":\"B\"},{\"corpo_clean\":\"anticipate possible outcomes;\",\"id\":9014584,\"corpo\":\"<p>anticipate possible outcomes;<p>\",\"ordem\":3,\"rotulo\":\"C\"},{\"corpo_clean\":\"clarify the previous statement;\",\"id\":9014585,\"corpo\":\"<p>clarify the previous statement;<p>\",\"ordem\":4,\"rotulo\":\"D\"},{\"corpo_clean\":\"provide an alternative argument.\",\"id\":9014586,\"corpo\":\"<p>provide an alternative argument.<p>\",\"ordem\":5,\"rotulo\":\"E\"}],\"grupoQuestao\":{\"enunciado_clean\":\"Internal audit\u2019s role in ESG reporting Conversations and focus on sustainability, typically grouped into environmental, social and governance (ESG) issues, are quickly evolving \u2014 from activist investor groups and inquisitive regulators pushing for change to governing bodies and C-suite executives struggling to understand and embrace the concept. At the forefront of this new risk area is pressure for organizations to make public commitments to sustainability and provide routine updates to ESG-related strategies, goals, and metrics that are accurate and relevant. However, ESG reporting is still immature, and there is not a lot of definitive guidance for organizations in this space. For example, there is no single standard for what should be reported. What is clear is that strong governance over ESG \u2014 as with effective governance overall \u2014 requires alignment among the principal players as outlined in The Internal Institute of Auditors (IIA) Three Lines Model. As with any risk area, internal audit should be well-positioned to support the governing body and management with objective assurance, insights, and advice on ESG matters. Embarking on the ESG journey Efforts to mitigate the accelerating effects of climate change and address perceived historical social inequities are two powerful issues driving change globally. These movements have enhanced awareness of how all organizations impact, influence, and interact with society and the environment. They also have spurred organizations to better recognize and manage ESG risks (i.e., risks associated with how organizations operate in respect to their impact on the world around them). This broad risk category includes areas that are dynamic and often driven by factors that can be difficult to measure objectively. Still, there is growing urgency for organizations to understand and manage ESG risks, particularly as investors and regulators focus on organizations producing high-quality reporting on sustainability efforts. What\u2019s more, that pressure is being reflected increasingly in executive performance as more organizations tie incentive compensation metrics to ESG goals. As ESG reporting becomes increasingly common, it should be treated with the same care as financial reporting. Organizations need to recognize that ESG reporting must be built on a strategically crafted system of internal controls and accurately reflect how an organization\u2019s ESG efforts relate to each other, the organization\u2019s finances, and value creation. Internal audit can and should play a significant role in an organization\u2019s ESG journey. It can add value in an advisory capacity by helping to identify and establish a functional ESG control environment. It also can offer critical assurance support by providing an independent and objective review of the effectiveness of ESG risk assessments, responses, and controls. Source: Adapted from https:na.theiia.orgabout-iaPublicDocumentsWhite-Paper-Internal-Audits-Role-in-ESG-Reporting.pdf\",\"id\":519876,\"enunciado\":\"<p style=text-align: center;>Internal audit\u2019s role in ESG reporting <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;>Conversations and focus on sustainability, typically grouped into environmental, social and governance (ESG) issues, are quickly evolving \u2014 from activist investor groups and inquisitive regulators pushing for change to governing bodies and C-suite executives struggling to understand and embrace the concept. At the forefront of this new risk area is pressure for organizations to make public commitments to sustainability and provide routine updates to ESG-related strategies, goals, and metrics that are accurate and relevant. However, ESG reporting is still immature, and there is not a lot of definitive guidance for organizations in this space. For example, there is no single standard for what should be reported. <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;>What is clear is that strong governance over ESG \u2014 as with effective governance overall \u2014 requires alignment among the principal players as outlined in The Internal Institute of Auditors (IIA) Three Lines Model. As with any risk area, internal audit should be well-positioned to support the governing body and management with objective assurance, insights, and advice on ESG matters. <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: center;>Embarking on the ESG journey <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;>Efforts to mitigate the accelerating effects of climate change and address perceived historical social inequities are two powerful issues driving change globally. These movements have enhanced awareness of how all organizations impact, influence, and interact with society and the environment. <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;>They also have spurred organizations to better recognize and manage ESG risks (i.e., risks associated with how organizations operate in respect to their impact on the world around them). This broad risk category includes areas that are dynamic and often driven by factors that can be difficult to measure objectively. <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;>Still, there is growing urgency for organizations to understand and manage ESG risks, particularly as investors and regulators focus on organizations producing high-quality reporting on sustainability efforts. What\u2019s more, that pressure is being reflected increasingly in executive performance as more organizations tie incentive compensation metrics to ESG goals. <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;>As ESG reporting becomes increasingly common, it should be treated with the same care as financial reporting. Organizations need to recognize that ESG reporting must be built on a strategically crafted system of internal controls and accurately reflect how an organization\u2019s ESG efforts relate to each other, the organization\u2019s finances, and value creation. <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;>Internal audit can and should play a significant role in an organization\u2019s ESG journey. It can add value in an advisory capacity by helping to identify and establish a functional ESG control environment. It also can offer critical assurance support by providing an independent and objective review of the effectiveness of ESG risk assessments, responses, and controls. <p><p style=text-align: justify;><br><p><p style=text-align: justify;><span style=font-size: 11px;>Source: Adapted from https:na.theiia.orgabout-iaPublicDocumentsWhite-Paper-Internal-Audits-Role-in-ESG-Reporting.pdf<span><p>\",\"rotulo\":null,\"texto\":null,\"descricao\":\"Quest\u00f5es 11 a 15\",\"ordem\":11},\"assuntos\":[{\"palavrasChave\":[],\"nome_clean\":\"L\u00edngua Inglesa\",\"oab\":false,\"nome\":\"L\u00edngua Inglesa\",\"pai\":null,\"assunto_raiz\":58,\"materia\":true,\"id\":58,\"slug\":\"lingua-inglesa\"},{\"palavrasChav